# How does the proximity of the epicenter to the border with Syria affect the regional seismic activity and potential cross-border impacts following the main quake in southern Turkey?

## Summary
The 7.8 magnitude earthquake that struck southern Turkey has had major cross-border impacts, with the epicenter's proximity to the Syrian border influencing regional seismic activity <font color=#FF3399>[1,2]</font>. The aftershocks have been felt over a stretch of more than 300 kilometers along the fault zone that ruptured in southern Turkey, extending from the border with Syria up through the province of Malatya <font color=#FF3399>[1,2]</font>. The United States Geological Survey has reported at least 43 significant aftershocks of 4.3 or greater magnitude that were felt in the earthquake zone, including a massive 7.5 magnitude earthquake north of the epicenter <font color=#FF3399>[2]</font>. This seismic activity has led to considerable destruction in both Turkey and Syria, with over 2,000 homes destroyed in Turkey and the extent of devastation in Syria yet to be determined <font color=#FF3399>[3]</font>. The continual aftershocks present people with the difficult choice of returning to potentially unstable homes or seeking shelter elsewhere, with severe cold weather further exacerbating the situation <font color=#FF3399>[3]</font>. In addition to the damage in Turkey, the earthquake and subsequent aftershocks have resulted in at least 1,451 deaths in Syria, particularly affecting the regions of Aleppo, Hama, Latakia, and Tartus (5

