|<font color=#FF3399>[5]</font> In neighboring Syria, at least 1,451 people have died.<a href="https://www.cnn.com/2023/02/05/europe/earthquake-hits-turkey-intl-hnk/index.html" target="_blank">Source</a>| One of the strongest earthquakes to hit the region in a century shook residents from their beds at around 4 a.m. on Monday, sending tremors as far away as Lebanon and Israel. In Turkey, at least 2,921 people were killed and more than 15,800 others injured, according to Turkeys head of disaster services, Yunus Sezer. In neighboring Syria, at least 1,451 people have died. According to the Syrian state news agency SANA, 711 people have died across government-controlled areas, mostly in the regions of Aleppo, Hama, Latakia, and Tartus.|
